# Capstone Data Model Conventions

## Proficiency Scale (1–5)

Used on `employee_skills.proficiency` and `project_requirements.min_proficiency`.

| Level | Label | Meaning |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | Beginner | Tutorial-level. Not ready for independent production work. |
| 2 | Familiar | Has done real work with it, needs guidance on complex tasks. |
| 3 | Proficient | Works independently on standard problems. Can own a feature. |
| 4 | Advanced | Makes architectural decisions, handles complexity, reviews others. |
| 5 | Expert | Go-to person. Designs systems, mentors others, spots non-obvious failure modes. |

## Setting `min_proficiency` on Project Requirements

| Scenario | min_proficiency |
|---|---|
| This skill IS the core of the project — wrong decisions here sink it | 4 |
| Skill is load-bearing but a proficient engineer can handle it | 3 |
| Supporting role — just can't be starting from zero | 2 |
| Never use in requirements | 5 |

## Headcount on Requirements

`headcount_needed` is expressed in **FTE (full-time equivalents)**. It represents how much of a person's time the project needs for this skill area — not a raw count of people.

| Value | Meaning |
|---|---|
| 1.0 | One person full-time on this skill |
| 0.5 | One person at 50% of their time |
| 0.8 | One person at 80% of their time |
| 1.5 | One full-time person + one half-time person |
| 2.0 | Two people full-time |

When evaluating fit: compare the candidate's available allocation % to the FTE needed. A candidate with 60% available bandwidth cannot cover a 0.8 FTE requirement.

## Gap Types (Three Distinct Cases)

Always distinguish these in LLM output — they require different recommendations:

- **True skill gap**: No employee meets `min_proficiency` for a required skill → needs hiring or training
- **Availability gap**: Qualified employees exist but are fully allocated before the project starts → timing problem, not a skills problem
- **Coverage risk**: Only one person qualifies for a critical skill → single point of failure even if no gap today

## Allocation Model

- `allocation_pct` on `allocations`: 0–100% of an employee's time on a project
- An employee is "available" for a new project if their total allocation across all active projects leaves headroom, and their current commitments end before the new project starts
- Always check `time_off` alongside `allocations` when computing availability

## Core Tables

```
employees           id, name, role, department, level, employment_type, start_date
skills              id, name, category (technical/domain/leadership)
employee_skills     employee_id, skill_id, proficiency (1-5), years_exp
projects            id, name, status (active/pipeline/completed), priority, start_date, end_date
project_requirements project_id, skill_id, min_proficiency, headcount_needed, start_date, end_date
allocations         id, employee_id, project_id, allocation_pct, start_date, end_date
time_off            employee_id, start_date, end_date, type
```

## Vector Store Documents

Employee profiles and project descriptions are embedded as **whole documents** (not chunked). Chunking loses coherence for self-contained profile bios. Metadata fields to always include: `type`, `employee_id` or `project_id`, `department`, `level`, `status`.
